      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Either this approach, using a <code>Comparator</code>, or @BMT&#39;s approach of making the objects implement <code>Comparable</code> would work. The difference is that by implementing <code>Comparable</code>, you&#39;re saying that the ordering is a fundamental part of the nature of the objects (like integers or strings), whereas by using a <code>Comparator</code>, you&#39;re saying that in this specific context, you want them ordered in a certain way."
